 The pipeline is:

  1. Tokenize — text is split into subword tokens (WordPiece/BPE). "overflow" → ["over", "##flow"]
  2. Transformer forward pass — each token gets a 384 (or 768) dimensional hidden state via
  self-attention across all layers
  3. Pooling — the per-token hidden states are collapsed into one vector. BAAI uses mean pooling
  (average all token vectors). The result is our embedding.
  4. L2 normalize — the vector is normalized to unit length so cosine similarity = dot product

  The dot product comes at query time, not during embedding creation. ChromaDB uses it to find nearest neighbors.
  ---
  nomic handles long documents much better (8192 vs 512 tokens). For
  our seed Q&A pairs that are short, BAAI is fine. If we start indexing long theory docs from
  python-services/prep/theory_refined/, BAAI will silently truncate anything past ~380 words — nomic won't.

  When to switch to nomic-embed

  - we're on a machine with ≥4 GB free RAM
  - we're indexing long documents (our .txt theory files)
  - we want better semantic quality on nuanced questions

  Switch by setting EMBED_MODEL=nomic-ai/nomic-embed-text-v1.5 in our .env, then wipe ChromaDB volume
  and run ./reload_rag.sh — the dimensions are incompatible so we can't mix vectors from both models
  in the same collection.